default&#xa0;
defaultWe are concerned by the proposal that criminal legal aid for prison law ma
defaulttters should be restricted to the criteria set out in the consultation paper, and that it is reliant on both an effective complaints system and on reasonable adjustments being made to ensure prisoners with learning difficulties and/or mental health problem
defaults can use the complaint system. Our 
defaultinspection evidence suggests a distinct lack of confidence in the prisoner complaints system, particularly amongst those prisoners reporting as having a disability or a mental health issue. It is our view that prisoners 
defaultwith identified communication, mental health problems and learning difficulties should be able to obtain legal aid on the current basis.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultAdditionally, any legal aid that is made available under these restrictions will have to be delivered 
defaultby provider
defaults 
defaultwith a criminal law contract.
default We do not cons
defaultider that this is appropriate. 
defaultMost 
defaultexisting prison law experts are 
defaultnot criminal practitioners, but individuals and firms who specialize in prison law
default which is 
defaulta niche form of public law.
default&#xa0;
defaultPdefaultroposal that providersdefault of legal services in applications for judicial review against public bodies should only be paid for work done on the case if the Court grants permission for the application to proceeddefault&#xa0;defaultThe EDF strongly disagrees with this proposal as it will weed out the 
defaultstrong
default cases as much as the weak ones;
default it will act as a disincentive to early settlement or resolution of cases and will discourage solicitors from taking any judicial review cases on behalf of individuals 
defaulthowever strong their case
default. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe EDF considers tha
defaultt Judicial Review is a vital remedy and one of the most important ways for individual people to hold national and local public bodies to 
defaultaccount for acting unlawfully. 
defaultWe note that the Ministry of Justice in its press release for the earlier Consultation o
defaultn Reforming Judicial Review acknowledged 
default‘the important role that Judicial Review plays in holding Government and others to account’.
default The power to judicially review public decisions is an important reserve power enabling citizens to ensure good governance 
defaultand further constraints on its use should be approached with considerable caution.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf this proposal goes ahead, it will create a situation where individuals will not be able to bring cases challenging the decisions of local authorities or central government because they will not be able to find lawyers willing to take the risk of not get
defaultting paid for this work. 
defaultIf, as seems likely, 
defaultlawyers stop doing this type of work people facing injustice because of public law failings by public bodies will find it increasingly difficult to find anyone to advise them.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is neither reasonable nor sens
defaultible to expect individuals to take judicial revie
defaultw action without legal advice. 
defaultLitigants acting without advice are more likely to take cases that will not succeed, whatever their intrinsic merits, because the case has
default not been adequately prepared. 
defaultThey ar
defaulte also more likely to take weak cases which might have been deterred by good legal
default advice at the outset. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAny lawyer who did bring these challenges to court would have to pursue the court proceedings to make sure they were paid for their work. This would 
defaultcreate a perverse incentive for cases to be pursued in court even when the initiation of judicial review is sufficient to persuade a public body to acknowledge its error and reconsider a decision (and there is ample evidence
default that this happens regularly). 
defaultL
defaultawyers will hav
defaulte
default an incentive to fight cases rather than to reach an early resolution 
defaultwhich will waste court time and ultimately cost public funds. We do not believe that this is good value for money nor does it assist the Government’s objective of securin
defaultg early settlement and preventing litigation wherever possible.
